f those oasis communities. Located in the western part of the Dakhla Oasis, it was an important regional center, reaching a peak in the Roman period before being abandoned. Over the past decade, excavations at this well-preserved site have revealed its urban layout and brought to light houses, streets, a bath, a school, and a church. The only standing brick pyramid of the Roman period in Egypt has been restored. Wall-paintings, temple reliefs, pottery, and texts all contribute to give a lively sense of its political, religious, economic, and cultural life. This book presents these aspects of the city’s existence and its close ties to the Nile valley, by way of long desert roads, in an accessible and richly illustrated fashion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zEgyptzAmheida Site. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Egypt.2bisacsh1 aAravecchia, Nicola, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBagnall, Roger S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCribiore, Raffaella, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKaper, Olaf E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKaper, Olaf E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcFadden, Susanna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479860319.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479860319423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479860319/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles